TY  - JOUR
T1  - Money and Credit Redux
AU  - Gu, Chao
AU  - Mattesini, Fabrizio
AU  - Wright, Randall
Y1  - 2016/01/01
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA12798
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 1
EP  - 32
VL  - 84
IS  - 1
KW  - Money
KW  - credit
KW  - debt
KW  - essentiality
KW  - neutrality
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA12798
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We analyze money and credit as competing payment instruments in decentralized exchange. In natural environments, we show the economy does not need both: if credit is easy, money is irrelevant; if credit is tight, money is essential, but credit becomes irrelevant. Changes in credit conditions are neutral because real balances respond endogenously to keep total liquidity constant. This is true for both exogenous and endogenous debt limits and policy limits, secured and unsecured lending, and general pricing mechanisms. While we show how to overturn some of these results, the benchmark model suggests credit might matter less than people think.
ER  - 

